  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The Indian government introduced the \u20b92000 note in November 2016 primarily as part of its demonetization initiative, which aimed to combat black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption. After the sudden withdrawal of the \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes in November 2016, the introduction of the \u20b92000 note served several purposes:\n\n1. **Higher Denomination for Convenience**: The \u20b92000 note was introduced to provide a higher denomination currency that would help ease the cash shortage that emerged after the demonetization of the higher-value notes. It allowed for larger transactions to be conducted with fewer notes.\n\n2. **Facilitating the Transition**: The introduction of the \u20b92000 note was intended to facilitate the transition to a new currency system while ensuring that the economy continued to function smoothly. It was part of the government's effort to reintroduce currency into circulation.\n\n3. **Countering Counterfeit Currency**: The new \u20b92000 note was designed with advanced security features to reduce the risk of counterfeiting, a significant issue with the older \u20b91000 notes.\n\n4. **Symbolic Change**: By introducing a new denomination rather than reissuing the \u20b91000 note, the government aimed to signal a fresh start in its fight against black money and to reinforce its commitment to reforming the financial system.\n\nUltimately, the decision to introduce the \u20b92000 note instead of a new \u20b91000 note was a strategic move to address the challenges posed by the demonetization efforts while also promoting a more transparent and accountable economy.",
